1
00:00:04,182 --> 00:00:25,025
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa

2
00:00:27,858 --> 00:00:44,598
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:47,883 --> 00:00:57,375
Yesterday we talked about the skills of meditation, how to become focused and one-pointed, attentive with a sharp intelligence.

4
00:00:58,451 --> 00:01:00,740
and what we find is that the mind rebels.

5
00:01:02,509 --> 00:01:08,935
All our hopes of quick success are dashed as the armies of Mara, the evil one, burst upon us.

6
00:01:10,501 --> 00:01:14,064
These, of course, are the so-called hindrances, the niwarana.

7
00:01:15,266 --> 00:01:23,474
I say they're so-called hindrances because, in vipassana, they're one of the areas of mental and emotional activity we have to observe.

8
00:01:24,796 --> 00:01:28,200
What they're a real hindrance to is a peaceful state of mind.

9
00:01:29,302 --> 00:01:38,432
They're really hindrances to attaining samatha, or a calm, mental, joyful state of mind that leads to the absorptions, the jhana.

10
00:01:40,387 --> 00:01:48,114
Here in Pure Vipassana, we're not concerned to fabricate or develop wonderful, spaced-out, ecstatic states of mind.

11
00:01:49,316 --> 00:01:51,076
If they come, all well and good.

12
00:01:52,159 --> 00:01:59,245
But even then, they're just objects to note and watch, feel and observe, experience and understand.

13
00:02:01,266 --> 00:02:02,709
So what are these hindrances?

14
00:02:03,510 --> 00:02:05,391
Well, I don't think they'll come as a surprise.

15
00:02:06,753 --> 00:02:10,056
The Buddha gave some apt imagery to go with the teachings.

16
00:02:11,133 --> 00:02:15,057
Imagine looking into a pool of water, the body, heart, mind.

17
00:02:16,318 --> 00:02:19,582
Suppose it's all kaleidoscopic with variegated colours.

18
00:02:20,805 --> 00:02:25,971
Well, you just can't see beyond these colours into the pool, and they entrance.

19
00:02:25,991 --> 00:02:27,552
That sends your desire for you.

20
00:02:28,875 --> 00:02:30,235
Suppose the water's boiling.

21
00:02:31,037 --> 00:02:32,699
You can't see into the pool then either.

22
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:36,364
That's aversion, hatred and anger.

23
00:02:37,676 --> 00:02:39,419
Then the pool is covered with mosses.

24
00:02:39,960 --> 00:02:44,026
That's the effect of sloth and torpor, dullness and lethargy.

25
00:02:45,989 --> 00:02:48,872
Suppose a wind blows across the pool and makes waves.

26
00:02:49,774 --> 00:02:51,776
You can't see into the depths then either.

27
00:02:52,979 --> 00:02:58,105
That's the effect of restlessness, anxiety and guilt, remorse.

28
00:02:59,687 --> 00:03:01,770
And finally the pool is turbid and muddy.

29
00:03:02,551 --> 00:03:05,997
That's the insidious pervasiveness of sceptical doubt.

30
00:03:07,883 --> 00:03:18,478
Here I'm not going to talk much about the area of sensual desire, because we've talked a little bit about it when it comes to eating, and I shall be giving further ideas as we progress.

31
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:28,092
But I'll tackle the subject in a couple of days, when all the pain and horror of settling in over these first three days finally subsides.

32
00:03:28,973 --> 00:03:31,997
And I promise newcomers, it does, it does subside.

33
00:03:32,318 --> 00:03:33,840
The old sloggers will tell you.

34
00:03:35,034 --> 00:03:41,528
So I'd like instead to tackle the whole problem of pain, which is what we're all probably going through to some degree or other right now.

35
00:03:43,171 --> 00:03:47,020
But first, let me just give one or two pointers about pleasure.

36
00:03:48,603 --> 00:03:52,950
Firstly, the fact is that sensual pleasure gives rise to happiness.

37
00:03:53,572 --> 00:03:55,836
That is a pleasant mental state.

38
00:03:57,038 --> 00:03:58,540
We have to make that distinction.

39
00:03:59,302 --> 00:04:04,211
Just because there's a pleasant taste on the tongue doesn't mean you have to get excited about it.

40
00:04:05,112 --> 00:04:08,299
Indeed, sometimes people feel quite negative when they eat.

41
00:04:09,477 --> 00:04:20,250
So separating happiness as a mental state from the pleasure, a physical state, allows us not to get caught up in fantasies that originate in sensual pleasure.

42
00:04:22,552 --> 00:04:27,139
The most obvious and obsessive, of course, are the ones around sex and romance.

43
00:04:27,158 --> 00:04:28,060
Hardly a surprise.

44
00:04:29,101 --> 00:04:32,365
And with this one especially, we have to be very careful.

45
00:04:32,685 --> 00:04:34,168
It can really take over.

46
00:04:35,379 --> 00:04:49,954
As always, the instruction is to note the fantasy for what it is, sexy, romantic, and so on, and turn your attention away, back to the breath, or if there are sexual feelings in the body, to those.

47
00:04:51,334 --> 00:04:57,081
Now, when you turn away, you have to stop for a moment and make the decision to abandon such thoughts.

48
00:04:58,482 --> 00:05:00,964
Sometimes you may feel the pull to go back there.

49
00:05:01,745 --> 00:05:03,447
That's the tanha, the attachment.

50
00:05:04,860 --> 00:05:08,884
If you can, stay with that subtle feeling until it dies away.

51
00:05:10,086 --> 00:05:15,591
In that way, you will disempower the habit of seeking happiness in sexual and romantic pleasure.

52
00:05:17,112 --> 00:05:23,718
Now, even if you can't make this a lifetime objective, at least you can do it for a few days or weeks that you're on this course.

53
00:05:25,879 --> 00:05:30,264
The second thing to understand is why sensual pleasure is so attractive.

54
00:05:31,444 --> 00:05:34,226
It's not just that it's pleasurable in itself.

55
00:05:35,201 --> 00:05:40,369
It is also that it provides an escape from unpleasurable and unhappy states.

56
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:43,814
Why else do we refer to comfort food?

57
00:05:45,255 --> 00:05:50,083
Feeling a bit bored, a bit lonely, nothing better than a piece of cake and a cup of coffee.

58
00:05:51,785 --> 00:05:56,110
So there is an underlying force that keeps us at the pleasurable obsession.

59
00:05:57,372 --> 00:06:04,062
Its job is to keep us away from pain and suffering, and that is a very great force in our psyche.

60
00:06:05,459 --> 00:06:09,423
I knew of two young men travelling around Sri Lanka who took drugs all the time.

61
00:06:10,245 --> 00:06:13,769
They even took tranquilizers when travelling on a long bus ride.

62
00:06:14,850 --> 00:06:18,095
They just didn't see the point of being even slightly uncomfortable.

63
00:06:19,516 --> 00:06:21,759
That's the sort of denial we can get into.

64
00:06:21,819 --> 00:06:33,153
Our job is not to escape the fact of unsatisfactoriness, the fact of discomfort and pain, and the fact of suffering in our lives.

65
00:06:33,353 --> 00:06:34,435
What a futile effort!

66
00:06:35,516 --> 00:06:38,961
But to find equanimity with the uncomfortable and the painful.

67
00:06:40,024 --> 00:06:45,773
And in so doing, we discover that this is the way to the end of unsatisfactoriness and suffering.

68
00:06:47,696 --> 00:06:57,572
This also means we have to find equanimity with the pleasurable, not to believe that transient pleasant feelings and sensations are something we can base our happiness on.

69
00:06:58,952 --> 00:07:05,560
I ask you why should our interior lives be so dominated by pleasant or unpleasant sensual feelings?

70
00:07:07,841 --> 00:07:12,045
So be careful when this trait to run away from the unpleasant arises.

71
00:07:12,867 --> 00:07:22,435
For instance, should you find abandoning thoughts of romance brings up feelings of loneliness, take that as an opportunity to investigate loneliness.

72
00:07:23,858 --> 00:07:28,081
Since we have escaped loneliness by indulging in romantic fantasy,

73
00:07:28,197 --> 00:07:33,144
When the loneliness dissolves, so the romantic fantasies lose some of their obsessiveness.

74
00:07:35,346 --> 00:07:43,637
So, whenever we find ourselves caught up in pleasing fantasies, really note, recognize and acknowledge them.

75
00:07:44,858 --> 00:07:47,663
Just for a moment, seize that reflection.

76
00:07:48,403 --> 00:07:49,285
This is romance.

77
00:07:49,586 --> 00:07:50,427
This is greed.

78
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:51,728
This is avarice.

79
00:07:52,449 --> 00:07:53,531
This is about fame.

80
00:07:53,971 --> 00:07:55,132
This is about power.

81
00:07:56,310 --> 00:08:00,074
Turn your attention away from the mind, into the body.

82
00:08:01,975 --> 00:08:07,180
Should you feel that pull to go back into the fantasy, stay there with that feeling.

83
00:08:08,362 --> 00:08:09,622
Wait till it dies away.

84
00:08:09,682 --> 00:08:15,309
Then return to the breath or other sensation or feeling that draws your attention.

85
00:08:17,250 --> 00:08:21,293
If you find yourself struggling and fighting and getting tense, then stop.

86
00:08:21,935 --> 00:08:22,535
Relax.

87
00:08:23,475 --> 00:08:24,437
Take a deep breath.

88
00:08:25,017 --> 00:08:25,557
Relax.

89
00:08:27,242 --> 00:08:33,490
The process is one of gently letting go, allowing it to arise and pass away.

90
00:08:36,374 --> 00:08:40,057
So I'd like now to go on to the second of the entrances, aversion.

91
00:08:40,839 --> 00:08:46,565
And I would like to centre on pain because that's what we all feel a great deal of when we start a course.

92
00:08:48,126 --> 00:08:51,250
There are two types of pain, physical and mental.

93
00:08:52,511 --> 00:08:56,777
When it comes to physical pain proper, then it's only natural that it should arise.

94
00:08:57,652 --> 00:09:00,759
In fact, it's nature's way of telling us that something is wrong.

95
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:03,063
Toothache, earache and so on.

96
00:09:04,687 --> 00:09:08,556
In meditation, there seems to be three common areas of physical pain.

97
00:09:09,739 --> 00:09:13,467
Pain in the knees, the back and the neck.

98
00:09:13,488 --> 00:09:15,491
It's often because of bad posture, by the way.

99
00:09:16,466 --> 00:09:27,784
But if the posture is correct, any pain we get will either be because the body is being made to sit correctly, and or the internal tensions are allowed to manifest.

100
00:09:29,307 --> 00:09:32,393
And they are all usually some form of suppressed emotions.

101
00:09:33,975 --> 00:09:40,765
So if the posture is good, there's really only one place where physical pain proper should arise, and that's at the knees.

102
00:09:41,768 --> 00:09:43,791
Whether you're sitting cross-legged or kneeling.

103
00:09:44,918 --> 00:09:55,453
and that will disappear once the tendons at the top of the leg stretch and allow the leg to lie more flat, or, in the case of kneeling, once the knees have got used to the pressure.

104
00:09:56,755 --> 00:10:02,244
We can ease all this with cushions, and you shouldn't be in the slightest way embarrassed by doing so.

105
00:10:03,645 --> 00:10:08,133
Now, our attitude as Vipassana meditators is not to fight pain.

106
00:10:09,014 --> 00:10:13,221
We're not trying to develop into masochistic self-mortificators.

107
00:10:13,471 --> 00:10:17,139
Nor are we trying to be macho, trying to prove we're not crybabies.

108
00:10:17,679 --> 00:10:18,282
I can take it.

109
00:10:18,822 --> 00:10:19,364
Give me more.

110
00:10:20,787 --> 00:10:24,595
The purpose we suffer pain gladly is to see how suffering arises.

111
00:10:25,597 --> 00:10:26,759
Is pain suffering?

112
00:10:27,542 --> 00:10:28,384
That's the question.

113
00:10:29,405 --> 00:10:33,554
And if it isn't suffering, then how can we suffer when there's pain?

114
00:10:34,666 --> 00:10:43,259
So our purpose is not to make the pain go away, to stare it out, so to speak, or worse, to blast it out with vigorous noting.

115
00:10:43,740 --> 00:10:45,985
Be careful here, it's a common tendency.

116
00:10:47,726 --> 00:11:00,268
What we want to do is to investigate our relationship to it, our relationship of aversion, that desire of wanting it to disappear, and the fear, that desire to run away from it.

117
00:11:01,447 --> 00:11:05,892
the fight-flight syndrome we see in any sentient being who is suffering pain.

118
00:11:07,735 --> 00:11:10,017
Are these sorts of responses necessary?

119
00:11:11,339 --> 00:11:19,870
Just as we discover that pleasure and happiness are not the same, so we have to discover that pain and unhappiness are not the same.

120
00:11:21,611 --> 00:11:24,775
Now there is one great advantage to pain for all of us.

121
00:11:25,697 --> 00:11:30,863
When pain does arise, in the knees for instance, it definitely draws our attention.

122
00:11:31,518 --> 00:11:33,221
That's the wonderful thing about pain.

123
00:11:34,022 --> 00:11:48,148
It makes us very attentive, and our ability to remain focused grows naturally, though it has to be said this sort of concentration is not very reliable, it's not very strong, since it's dependent on a loud stimulus.

124
00:11:49,610 --> 00:11:54,960
Yet if only for this reason, the ardent meditator rejoices at the appearance of pain.

125
00:11:56,357 --> 00:11:57,198
So what do we do?

126
00:11:57,980 --> 00:11:58,541
Well, we note.

127
00:11:58,821 --> 00:11:59,721
Pain, pain.

128
00:12:00,263 --> 00:12:04,128
And our attention beelines in on the physical sensations.

129
00:12:05,610 --> 00:12:11,518
As it does so, it notices the emotional reaction of aversion and all the thinking that comes up.

130
00:12:12,219 --> 00:12:13,019
It hurts.

131
00:12:13,039 --> 00:12:13,841
I can't stand it.

132
00:12:14,341 --> 00:12:15,302
Why should I suffer this?

133
00:12:16,163 --> 00:12:17,085
It might be doing damage.

134
00:12:17,465 --> 00:12:18,466
My knee could implode.

135
00:12:20,308 --> 00:12:24,794
As the attention becomes aware of that, it notes aversion, aversion.

136
00:12:25,956 --> 00:12:32,326
Then we begin to see how the self wants to indulge the suggestions of aversion, to move and relieve the pain.

137
00:12:33,847 --> 00:12:46,985
We need to work with this vicious cycle, the physical pain, the emotional reaction and the dialogue, and the desire to act by way of aversion, each feeding off the other.

138
00:12:48,366 --> 00:12:56,255
the meditator begins to realize the separateness of the physical from the mental base, and yet their utter interdependence.

139
00:12:57,317 --> 00:13:02,244
They see clearly how suffering arises because of a wrong relationship to pain.

140
00:13:04,625 --> 00:13:07,028
Now it may be that pain becomes too severe.

141
00:13:07,089 --> 00:13:12,375
Then fear screams, the knee will crack, the tendons will snap, I'll never walk again.

142
00:13:13,998 --> 00:13:17,682
Can we stay right there at least for a while to see how it all works?

143
00:13:18,471 --> 00:13:24,461
Now we have to be sensible about this and know when to yield gracefully, as it were, to body messages.

144
00:13:25,344 --> 00:13:27,908
We don't have to break our knees to become enlightened.

145
00:13:29,431 --> 00:13:36,022
So here's the reason we must learn to sit patiently with pain, to bear patiently, to endure.

146
00:13:36,101 --> 00:13:40,909
The Buddha said that patience was the highest form of ascetic practice.

147
00:13:41,871 --> 00:13:44,495
And he asks us to bring this virtue to perfection.

148
00:13:45,741 --> 00:13:59,600
He says, even if someone were to start sawing you limb from limb with a double-handed saw, and if for a moment you indulge in thoughts of hatred and revenge, then you are not following his teachings.

149
00:14:00,562 --> 00:14:01,604
A tall order indeed.

150
00:14:02,804 --> 00:14:15,241
And we shall understand how he can ask such a thing when we see how the reaction of aversion and fear are the true suffering, and that pain is, in the end, just physical sensation.

151
00:14:16,522 --> 00:14:34,403
When we see this, really experience it and begin to allow the aversion and fear to subside instead of identifying with them and so not react to them, not to be hijacked by them, we are slowly but surely taking the suffering out of pain.

152
00:14:35,745 --> 00:14:40,431
Interestingly enough, if pain is watched long enough, it may very well disappear.

153
00:14:41,731 --> 00:14:46,477
Either the reason for it passes or the body creates its own painkillers.

154
00:14:46,828 --> 00:14:49,211
But let that sort of thing happen by itself.

155
00:14:50,032 --> 00:14:51,513
Don't try to make it happen.

156
00:14:52,693 --> 00:15:01,562
If you find yourself gritting your teeth and struggling with pain, the pain will get worse, for that reaction simply adds more turbulence.

157
00:15:01,581 --> 00:15:07,668
And if we are victorious, it will simply mean we've suppressed it all, and that's trouble stored up for the future.

158
00:15:09,570 --> 00:15:15,434
So now we've come to a point where we've decided we can't take any more and we have to move.

159
00:15:16,562 --> 00:15:19,289
here is another wonderful opportunity for insight.

160
00:15:20,592 --> 00:15:25,625
First, we note the intention, intending to move, intending to move.

161
00:15:26,788 --> 00:15:33,947
Then we slowly, ever so slowly, move from one posture to another, noting all the while.

162
00:15:34,282 --> 00:15:48,125
we experience the lessening of the physical pain, and we are attentive to the changing emotions, the relief, the joy, the comfort that arises, and all the dialogue, the sighs.

163
00:15:48,926 --> 00:15:55,797
We finally settle into another posture and feel so comfortable that we can return to noting and feeling the breath.

164
00:15:57,139 --> 00:15:58,140
Ah, what contentment!

165
00:15:58,480 --> 00:16:00,745
Now this is what meditation is all about.

166
00:16:02,446 --> 00:16:10,015
Then there it starts, a little tingling as it were, then a slight discomfort, and before long those damn knees are at it again.

167
00:16:10,076 --> 00:16:12,099
Is there no peace?

168
00:16:13,160 --> 00:16:14,182
And so it goes on, you see.

169
00:16:15,484 --> 00:16:19,288
Here we're experiencing the roller coaster of the pain-pleasure syndrome.

170
00:16:20,250 --> 00:16:21,150
Can we get off it?

171
00:16:21,652 --> 00:16:26,077
Can we take the suffering out of pain and the indulgence out of pleasure?

172
00:16:27,580 --> 00:16:28,360
Well, of course we can.

173
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:29,802
Of course we can.

174
00:16:30,778 --> 00:16:42,793
We do it so long as we can retain the observation post, that aloofness, that inner solitude above the madding crowd of our sensations, feelings and thoughts.

175
00:16:43,793 --> 00:16:44,654
And how do we do this?

176
00:16:45,495 --> 00:16:59,030
By turning upon everything in the attitude of the interested scientist, the one who wants to know how it all works, and in this instance, what is pain, what is suffering,

177
00:16:59,010 --> 00:17:01,956
Is pain suffering or is it something else?

178
00:17:02,719 --> 00:17:05,384
And how can suffering be brought to an end?

179
00:17:07,307 --> 00:17:15,265
And this leads us directly into another area of physical pain, the pain, the discomfort in the body caused by emotions.

180
00:17:16,747 --> 00:17:23,432
Mental states express themselves in the body and the physical electrochemical base reacts.

181
00:17:23,752 --> 00:17:24,453
We all know that.

182
00:17:25,134 --> 00:17:27,616
Stress gives us cramped shoulders and headaches.

183
00:17:28,176 --> 00:17:31,160
Anxiety makes us feel queasy and gives us ulcers.

184
00:17:31,941 --> 00:17:33,142
And so on.

185
00:17:33,162 --> 00:17:35,923
These emotions are products of past behavior.

186
00:17:36,805 --> 00:17:39,448
Please don't think the meditation is fabricating them.

187
00:17:40,228 --> 00:17:42,651
Stuff comes up fairly fast and heavy.

188
00:17:43,211 --> 00:17:45,353
And at times one wonders...

189
00:17:45,333 --> 00:17:47,996
Would I be suffering this if I weren't doing meditation?

190
00:17:49,176 --> 00:17:55,323
Well, you probably wouldn't be suffering them, not so sharply anyway, but they're still there, locked in the system.

191
00:17:56,284 --> 00:18:00,488
Vipassana simply unlocks them and allows them to express themselves.

192
00:18:01,769 --> 00:18:09,017
In fact, when you start meditating, it's a bit like lifting the lid off a dustbin, the lid of suppressive tendencies.

193
00:18:09,998 --> 00:18:11,919
And what are these suppressive tendencies?

194
00:18:12,779 --> 00:18:14,461
Why, aversion and fear, of course.

195
00:18:15,775 --> 00:18:21,500
Who wants to feel the heaviness of depression, the burning of jealousy, the sickliness of anxiety?

196
00:18:21,961 --> 00:18:22,381
No one.

197
00:18:22,942 --> 00:18:24,423
Best to keep them locked up in the body.

198
00:18:25,403 --> 00:18:26,605
But we know they're doing damage.

199
00:18:27,506 --> 00:18:29,627
Surely it's best to let them out into the open.

200
00:18:30,249 --> 00:18:31,970
Give them air so they can evaporate.

201
00:18:33,050 --> 00:18:34,452
And what is that open air?

202
00:18:35,594 --> 00:18:38,016
That is but the spaciousness of our own awareness.

203
00:18:38,757 --> 00:18:42,660
And when we do that, we begin to realize that this is therapeutic.

204
00:18:43,181 --> 00:18:45,343
This is the way the heart heals itself.

205
00:18:46,301 --> 00:18:48,904
and that the healing has to be a conscious process.

206
00:18:49,885 --> 00:18:52,750
Such emotions have to burn out in consciousness.

207
00:18:53,349 --> 00:18:55,113
We have to suffer them gladly.

208
00:18:55,153 --> 00:19:00,078
That's why we have to learn to sit patiently amidst the flames.

209
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:04,183
But why do they have to burn out in consciousness?

210
00:19:04,503 --> 00:19:07,667
Why can't emotions just die away quietly somewhere?

211
00:19:08,828 --> 00:19:12,814
For all intents and purposes, we cannot separate the body and the mind.

212
00:19:13,515 --> 00:19:16,258
They interreact intimately.

213
00:19:16,558 --> 00:19:27,534
So when the mind has turbulence in it, which isn't allowed to express itself, it gets buried into the cellular life and starts expressing itself there through physical symptoms.

214
00:19:28,655 --> 00:19:34,282
Just because we're not aware of repressed emotions doesn't mean they're not there, and doing damage.

215
00:19:35,064 --> 00:19:37,807
That's the reason we have psychosomatic illnesses.

216
00:19:39,172 --> 00:19:45,665
Often, through the meditation, because these turbulences are allowed to come out, such diseases are cured.

217
00:19:46,888 --> 00:19:56,910
This is one reason, from a health point of view, why we have to let those flames burn, why we have to train ourselves to feel the scorch and smile.

218
00:19:58,982 --> 00:20:05,592
Now when these negative emotions arise and are felt in the body, we find we have the same reaction as to pain.

219
00:20:06,534 --> 00:20:16,468
And yet again, we note, feel, observe, experience and come to understand how we always want to fight or run away from unpleasantness.

220
00:20:17,291 --> 00:20:24,207
Yet again the question arises, is the original emotion coming up pain or suffering?

221
00:20:25,390 --> 00:20:29,679
Or are the reactions of aversion and fear pain or suffering?

222
00:20:30,780 --> 00:20:32,084
How does suffering arise?

223
00:20:33,247 --> 00:20:35,672
Can we take the suffering out of pain?

224
00:20:36,563 --> 00:20:50,373
Can we so position ourselves that we can see, feel, experience the original pain or emotion and also see, feel, experience the reaction of aversion or fear towards it?

225
00:20:51,515 --> 00:20:54,201
And when we're in that position, is there suffering?

226
00:20:57,032 --> 00:21:05,442
Finally, there are emotions in the body, emotions that are so blocked and severely repressed that all we will ever feel is physical pain.

227
00:21:06,404 --> 00:21:08,712
Headaches and backaches are sometimes like this.

228
00:21:09,807 --> 00:21:11,849
but it could be pain virtually anywhere.

229
00:21:11,869 --> 00:21:25,950
Again, we observe the process of aversion and fear, allowing the pain to be just pain, to allow it to express, to expend, to release its malevolent energy.

230
00:21:26,611 --> 00:21:27,511
That's the cure.

231
00:21:29,595 --> 00:21:33,621
There was a dramatic incident recorded at the Mahasi Center in Rangoon.

232
00:21:34,444 --> 00:21:38,777
A man came with terminal cancer, refusing to take medication.

233
00:21:39,538 --> 00:21:40,801
He just sat with the pain.

234
00:21:41,944 --> 00:21:47,661
As he describes it, there was an explosion in the stomach and the cancer vanished.

235
00:21:49,075 --> 00:21:54,563
Now, whenever I tell this story, I like to add very quickly that Vipassana is not a cure-all.

236
00:21:55,223 --> 00:22:06,080
And as I said yesterday, on the one hand, if you practice for the sake of health, you will lose the spiritual aim, and on the other, if you don't get better, you will lose faith in the meditation.

237
00:22:07,462 --> 00:22:09,425
Let Vipassana do what it wants to do.

238
00:22:10,047 --> 00:22:14,053
Keep that deceiving self, the fiendish Mara, out of the way.

239
00:22:15,636 --> 00:22:16,917
Now, isn't it wonderful?

240
00:22:17,558 --> 00:22:28,107
Have you noticed that every time we talk about curing the heart of all her emotional problems, it's always in conjunction with just watching, just feeling.

241
00:22:28,147 --> 00:22:34,292
And when we're just experiencing like this, we're doing nothing, nothing at all.

242
00:22:34,913 --> 00:22:36,035
That's the wonder of it.

243
00:22:36,996 --> 00:22:43,101
If we just leave the heart alone, just get out of the way for once, she does it all by herself.

244
00:22:43,661 --> 00:22:45,643
She doesn't need any help from us.

245
00:22:45,623 --> 00:22:53,854
The heart can cure herself of all the illnesses we've intentionally or unintentionally caused by our greed, hatred and delusion.

246
00:22:54,535 --> 00:22:55,174
Have faith.

247
00:22:55,816 --> 00:23:01,723
There are powers in us beyond our control and they're working always towards our well-being.

248
00:23:04,086 --> 00:23:06,410
The next big hindrance is dullness and lethargy.

249
00:23:07,250 --> 00:23:10,315
First, I'd like to link this with restlessness.

250
00:23:11,424 --> 00:23:16,029
As far as I've come to experience it, these are two sides of the same coin.

251
00:23:17,030 --> 00:23:22,435
It's like fission and fusion energy or black holes and exploding stars.

252
00:23:23,938 --> 00:23:31,965
The turbulence in our psyche can either go inward and make us feel tired and drawn or outward into restless energy.

253
00:23:33,307 --> 00:23:41,095
Interestingly, there's a condition called restless depression where the person feels depressed and yet needs to move about restlessly.

254
00:23:42,239 --> 00:23:48,006
So we'll often experience these two states even in one sitting, sometimes one after the other.

255
00:23:49,607 --> 00:23:57,076
Even in daily life we can be feeling down one minute, then a friend calls and suddenly we're rushing all over the place getting ready to go out.

256
00:23:59,019 --> 00:24:03,285
Secondly, we mustn't confuse dullness and lethargy with laziness.

257
00:24:05,779 --> 00:24:16,037
Dullness refers to porridge head, when the mind feels like sludge, and lethargy refers to the physical heaviness we feel, the body feels like a slug.

258
00:24:17,278 --> 00:24:26,775
Occasionally the one comes without the other, but both are products of past conditioning, sometimes because we have been lazy in the past.

259
00:24:26,755 --> 00:24:34,125
Sometimes because we've used sleep to annihilate ourselves when the going gets too hard, or things upset us, and so on.

260
00:24:35,047 --> 00:24:37,892
So here we are back to that old duality.

261
00:24:38,593 --> 00:24:44,741
We enjoy sleeping, at least there's no pain in oblivion, and we wake up refreshed.

262
00:24:44,761 --> 00:24:48,467
But we also often use it to escape unhappy states.

263
00:24:50,210 --> 00:24:50,990
Consider.

264
00:24:51,375 --> 00:24:57,324
When we're children and we're naughty or weepy, our parents say it's because we're tired, and it's probably true.

265
00:24:58,226 --> 00:25:00,087
And what we need is a little sleep.

266
00:25:00,808 --> 00:25:06,277
So we learn early on that one way to escape painful feelings is to go to sleep.

267
00:25:06,718 --> 00:25:08,721
And hey presto, you wake up refreshed.

268
00:25:09,461 --> 00:25:10,884
Or at least you do most of the time.

269
00:25:12,226 --> 00:25:20,336
But this sort of sleep is a suppressive measure, a conscious effort to force the unpleasant out of the mind by radically ignoring it,

270
00:25:21,380 --> 00:25:23,282
And where has all that unpleasant energy gone?

271
00:25:24,125 --> 00:25:27,750
Surely it's stored somewhere to reappear on some cloudy day.

272
00:25:27,810 --> 00:25:37,988
Now, dullness and lethargy can be caused by any repressed or suppressed emotion, in which case they can arise with feelings of depression.

273
00:25:38,355 --> 00:25:51,569
So whatever the cause, and remember we're not concerned to find ultimate causes, dullness and lethargy, when they arise, have to be dealt with in such a way that the energy is allowed to disperse itself.

274
00:25:52,911 --> 00:26:01,440
And we do that by making the sensations and feelings, the objects to be observed and felt, experienced and understood.

275
00:26:02,340 --> 00:26:04,042
It's as simple as that.

276
00:26:05,743 --> 00:26:12,978
Two of the first few disciples of the Buddha, who were later to be seen as his most important, were Sariputta and Moggallana.

277
00:26:14,280 --> 00:26:17,626
Now Sariputta took a whole two weeks to become enlightened.

278
00:26:18,528 --> 00:26:24,359
It took this long, it said, because he wanted to investigate every bit of the path on the way.

279
00:26:25,538 --> 00:26:35,875
In the end, such was his grasp of the Dharma that he became known as the general of the Dharma, and the Buddha acknowledged him as second only to himself in understanding.

280
00:26:37,176 --> 00:26:40,563
Moggallana, however, was not so intellectually inclined.

281
00:26:41,443 --> 00:26:48,576
He was more of a magician, able to exercise psychic powers, again second only to the Buddha.

282
00:26:49,972 --> 00:26:55,061
When he began to meditate, the one big hindrance that came up was doneness and lethargy.

283
00:26:56,144 --> 00:27:06,122
So great were they that he had to ask the Buddha for guidance, and on this account, it is said, he became enlightened in only one week.

284
00:27:06,143 --> 00:27:08,606
So what were the directions the Buddha gave?

285
00:27:09,176 --> 00:27:22,390
Well, first, he told Moggallana not to take any notice, but at the first signs of dullness and lethargy, to simply put more energy into the practice, put more energy into the posture, lift up that spine.

286
00:27:23,810 --> 00:27:28,455
If attacked again, to consider the Dharma, to recognize the danger of this hindrance.

287
00:27:29,836 --> 00:27:34,442
This dread of consequences should lift up the energy enough to stay awake till it passes.

288
00:27:35,586 --> 00:27:45,481
If that failed to recite the Dharma, give the mind something simple to do like repeating the verses of the Dharma and so dispel the torpor.

289
00:27:45,501 --> 00:27:56,598
On one meditation course, I was suffering from this so much I decided to repeat the times tables and I got as far as 17 both forward and backward over a period of several days mind.

290
00:27:57,692 --> 00:28:06,923
My teacher at the time, Sayadaw Ujjanaka, told me that was skillful, but I think it would probably have been better to recite the discourses, if I'd have known any.

291
00:28:09,287 --> 00:28:12,009
If this should fail, it's time to do something.

292
00:28:14,192 --> 00:28:16,835
The Buddha advised Moggallana to rub his ears.

293
00:28:17,516 --> 00:28:26,906
Now at first that seems a little odd, but then, when we remember there are all those acupuncture points in the ears that affect every organ, it's definitely worth trying.

294
00:28:28,085 --> 00:28:29,890
If that fails, rub the legs.

295
00:28:31,294 --> 00:28:32,897
So now we've changed our posture.

296
00:28:34,101 --> 00:28:36,867
Then get up and wash the face in cold water.

297
00:28:38,092 --> 00:28:41,200
Sit in light or look at the light with the eyes open.

298
00:28:41,567 --> 00:28:47,836
then, which works only for those who've practiced concentration meditation, create a light source in the mind itself.

299
00:28:48,916 --> 00:28:55,505
Moggallana would have been adept at this, but for us, we would probably go on to the next, which is to walk up and down.

300
00:28:55,565 --> 00:29:09,701
And then, only then, when after nine different efforts, still the lethargy and dullness is pressing down, can we consider redefining it as tiredness, and so take a rest.

301
00:29:11,217 --> 00:29:18,530
The Buddha's advice shows us how persistent and also how gently we have to parry the blows of these hindrances.

302
00:29:19,333 --> 00:29:24,501
And we have to be inventive too, for what worked one time often doesn't have the same effect again.

303
00:29:24,561 --> 00:29:31,655
Remember, only after nine determined efforts can we take a rest.

304
00:29:33,272 --> 00:29:36,837
Taking these ideas as a standard, we can work out our own.

305
00:29:36,897 --> 00:29:40,983
As for myself, at the first signs I note more rapidly.

306
00:29:41,825 --> 00:29:43,867
I can put more energy into the posture.

307
00:29:44,970 --> 00:29:48,074
At the second, I take sloth as an object to observe.

308
00:29:48,374 --> 00:29:50,978
I note, feel its texture, observe it.

309
00:29:52,257 --> 00:29:56,642
Thirdly, if it comes back, I keep doing this but with the eyes open.

310
00:29:57,321 --> 00:29:59,003
Letting in light often wakes you up.

311
00:30:00,045 --> 00:30:05,790
But the eyes, which you can keep wide open, are turned towards the ground a couple of feet or so ahead.

312
00:30:07,071 --> 00:30:11,876
You can also look through a window or at a light, but there's danger of being distracted.

313
00:30:12,898 --> 00:30:14,420
So be careful not to look around.

314
00:30:16,102 --> 00:30:19,125
Then I'll stand and perhaps do a quiet stretch.

315
00:30:19,442 --> 00:30:22,547
Finally, if it's just too heavy, I'll do walking meditation.

316
00:30:23,688 --> 00:30:33,419
Not to beat it by walking fast, but to stay awake, still feeling the dullness and the lethargy fully, still allowing it to dissipate its energy.

317
00:30:35,241 --> 00:30:44,893
And if I do walking meditation with dullness and lethargy, I don't do it slowly, but at a normal pace, just keeping the attention on the feelings in the body.

318
00:30:46,897 --> 00:30:50,584
Alternatively, I can just decide to struggle with it on the cushion.

319
00:30:51,506 --> 00:30:53,849
I just keep gently pushing up against it.

320
00:30:54,671 --> 00:31:00,181
I may fall asleep, but as soon as I wake, I make this effort to straighten up and just keep sitting.

321
00:31:01,343 --> 00:31:04,588
The danger of this is that I can give in and fall asleep properly.

322
00:31:05,369 --> 00:31:12,281
But usually, if you fall into sleep in a meditation posture, the body jerks forward and that's enough to waken you.

323
00:31:13,712 --> 00:31:19,700
And sometimes you may find yourself in that strange world of neither asleep nor awake, and the body swaying.

324
00:31:21,422 --> 00:31:28,872
There was also a time, something I picked up from another monk, when I sat facing a wall, in really old Bodhidharma style.

325
00:31:30,032 --> 00:31:37,442
Some of you may know the legend of the great Bodhidharma, with an R by the way, to whom Zen is accredited.

326
00:31:37,422 --> 00:31:39,763
He sat for nine years facing a wall.

327
00:31:40,724 --> 00:31:44,407
When you face a wall in meditation and you fall asleep, bang!

328
00:31:44,888 --> 00:31:46,430
Boy, does that head hit that brick.

329
00:31:47,290 --> 00:31:51,555
And do you know, this stuff can be so heavy, you still keep falling asleep.

330
00:31:52,635 --> 00:31:55,979
Well, after a few bangs, I began to sense brain damage.

331
00:31:57,220 --> 00:31:59,041
I did eventually find a kinder way.

332
00:31:59,501 --> 00:32:06,888
I used to sit under a mosquito net, and just the gentle brush of the net against the forehead would be enough to startle me from sleep.

333
00:32:08,319 --> 00:32:14,428
My teacher then, said Eugenica, used to call dullness and lethargy my two very good friends.

334
00:32:14,929 --> 00:32:15,769
And they are, aren't they?

335
00:32:16,069 --> 00:32:16,651
You'll hear them.

336
00:32:17,612 --> 00:32:18,794
Oh, you're so tired.

337
00:32:19,355 --> 00:32:20,435
You've not had enough sleep.

338
00:32:21,116 --> 00:32:23,079
You aren't ready for such rigorous training.

339
00:32:23,840 --> 00:32:27,726
What you need is a little kip, a ziz, a power nap.

340
00:32:27,746 --> 00:32:28,887
You'll feel so much better.

341
00:32:29,669 --> 00:32:30,710
You always do.

342
00:32:32,031 --> 00:32:34,394
Ten minutes, and you wake up two hours later.

343
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:37,623
So, refuse to be annihilated.

344
00:32:38,023 --> 00:32:40,185
Refuse to be annihilated.

345
00:32:42,067 --> 00:32:45,451
Now, some of you may think we don't get enough sleep.

346
00:32:45,471 --> 00:32:47,555
But it does take a day or two to lift the energy.

347
00:32:48,536 --> 00:32:51,940
But we're hardly doing anything strenuous, physically or mentally.

348
00:32:52,540 --> 00:32:54,383
It's not as though we're out there digging roads.

349
00:32:55,124 --> 00:32:56,444
We're not working out accounts.

350
00:32:57,145 --> 00:32:59,808
We don't have to deal with fractious people.

351
00:32:59,890 --> 00:33:08,060
The whole situation here is one of outward calm, taking our time, the joy of knowing we have nothing to achieve, nowhere to go.

352
00:33:08,101 --> 00:33:13,808
And since we're not communicating, we don't even have to be somebody, a personality.

353
00:33:14,990 --> 00:33:19,856
If only on account of that, we don't need as much sleep as we might in ordinary daily life.

354
00:33:21,742 --> 00:33:30,531
Some of you may know we sleep in one and three quarter hour rhythms, and it's the first two only where we actually sleep at the deepest of four levels.

355
00:33:31,452 --> 00:33:33,955
After that, we never sleep so deeply again.

356
00:33:34,856 --> 00:33:42,625
So decide that the five and a half hour sleep is enough, and honestly recognize any so-called tiredness as dullness and lethargy.

357
00:33:43,405 --> 00:33:46,388
Work against them, and so lift up your energy level.

358
00:33:47,049 --> 00:33:48,832
You'll see, it's like running.

359
00:33:49,511 --> 00:33:50,973
You suddenly get second wind.

360
00:33:52,269 --> 00:33:59,025
In a longer course, you could all reduce your sleep to less than four hours, and sometimes go through a day or two without sleep.

361
00:33:59,547 --> 00:34:03,194
So calming and energizing can this vipassana meditation be.

362
00:34:03,234 --> 00:34:09,789
Now I mentioned earlier that dullness and lethargy are not to be confused with laziness.

363
00:34:10,782 --> 00:34:15,929
If by laziness, we mean an actual decision not to put energy into what we're doing.

364
00:34:16,990 --> 00:34:26,003
Laziness is the obvious enemy of effort, and we can say our meditation period has been poor if we don't work against the tendency to be lazy.

365
00:34:27,766 --> 00:34:39,101
Of course, the more we give in to laziness, the more we add to the store of conditioned laziness, which is one of the factors that go to make up dullness and lethargy in the first place.

366
00:34:39,907 --> 00:34:45,735
And the more we fail to work up our energy, the more difficult it will be to raise energy in the future.

367
00:34:46,815 --> 00:34:48,978
Remember, it's all about conditioning.

368
00:34:50,981 --> 00:34:55,025
They say Margaret Thatcher only slept four hours a night while in office.

369
00:34:56,085 --> 00:34:57,668
Now this is not a political statement.

370
00:34:58,989 --> 00:34:59,811
Anyway, beware.

371
00:35:00,831 --> 00:35:08,159
Let sloth and torpor, dullness and lethargy come and go and under no circumstance make a decision to be lazy.

372
00:35:10,469 --> 00:35:12,070
So now we come to restlessness.

373
00:35:12,652 --> 00:35:13,193
It's the same.

374
00:35:14,394 --> 00:35:18,099
Always do the opposite to what the hindrance is advising you to do.

375
00:35:19,242 --> 00:35:21,063
Sloth suggests you take a nap.

376
00:35:21,965 --> 00:35:24,809
Restlessness suggests you walk about and do something.

377
00:35:25,731 --> 00:35:26,152
But don't.

378
00:35:26,853 --> 00:35:29,215
Refuse to be a slave to these dictators.

379
00:35:29,637 --> 00:35:30,177
Refuse.

380
00:35:30,777 --> 00:35:31,039
Sit.

381
00:35:31,800 --> 00:35:32,300
Sit still.

382
00:35:33,181 --> 00:35:36,746
Observe that feeling and how we react with aversion.

383
00:35:37,250 --> 00:35:45,822
Note, feel, experience, observe both the dislike we have of it and the desire we have to appease it.

384
00:35:46,884 --> 00:35:56,137
Make that little vicious circle the object to understand, the physical feelings, the mental state and the relationship we have of aversion.

385
00:35:57,601 --> 00:36:05,231
Slowly, the discomfort of being with restlessness will lessen and we'll be able to sit still even amidst a tornado.

386
00:36:06,797 --> 00:36:08,880
Another thing you can do is scan the body.

387
00:36:09,422 --> 00:36:20,478
Start from the top of the head and just pass your consciousness through every part all the way down to the tip of your toes and back up again and just see where restlessness is actually felt.

388
00:36:21,601 --> 00:36:24,244
Do we really feel restless at the end of our noses?

389
00:36:25,586 --> 00:36:34,981
Just moving the consciousness up and down the body like this can have a calming effect but don't do it for that reason for then we lose our spiritual purpose.

390
00:36:35,452 --> 00:36:38,847
And we fall into the trap of trying to establish a comfort zone.

391
00:36:39,771 --> 00:36:45,175
We do it to observe, to watch, to feel, to experience and to understand.

392
00:36:46,657 --> 00:36:57,916
If, however, the restlessness gets too much and we decide to move our posture, well, just as we move out of pain, note intending to move, intending to move.

393
00:36:58,657 --> 00:37:08,496
Move very slowly, noting, feeling, observing, experiencing all the different changes in posture, sensations and emotions as you do so.

394
00:37:10,163 --> 00:37:18,355
If restlessness is only in the mind, thoughts tumbling one after the other, obsessive thinking, then we need to be patient.

395
00:37:19,456 --> 00:37:24,543
Every time we wake up out of a stream of thought or daydream, note the content.

396
00:37:25,485 --> 00:37:27,989
Lust, ambition, worry and so on.

397
00:37:28,989 --> 00:37:32,795
And gently but firmly bring the attention back to the breath.

398
00:37:33,907 --> 00:37:36,273
But the intention must be very empowered.

399
00:37:36,994 --> 00:37:42,788
It must be a resolute intention, a determined determination to observe the breath.

400
00:37:44,331 --> 00:37:52,371
Alternatively, you may look into the heart center and see if you can identify, feel and note the emotions which are impelling the thoughts.

401
00:37:53,447 --> 00:37:58,800
Actually, I always find this most productive, for all thought has an emotive value.

402
00:37:59,802 --> 00:38:04,373
However, sometimes the mind is just frivolous and simply needs to be tamed.

403
00:38:05,494 --> 00:38:08,402
The meditator must decide this for themselves.

404
00:38:10,356 --> 00:38:12,820
The final hindrance is skeptical doubt.

405
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:16,264
This can become a serious spiritual disease.

406
00:38:17,063 --> 00:38:21,969
Actually, such doubts can undermine our work, our relationships, our whole life.

407
00:38:22,891 --> 00:38:25,273
It's the sort of thing that stops you doing.

408
00:38:25,853 --> 00:38:30,438
It's a fear, a fear of failure, a lack of confidence, a lack of trust.

409
00:38:30,940 --> 00:38:33,543
We question everything, but we won't try it.

410
00:38:35,164 --> 00:38:37,427
Suppose you go to a doctor with an ailment.

411
00:38:37,559 --> 00:38:39,021
but you're not sure of the doctor.

412
00:38:40,001 --> 00:38:45,407
You feel you've not been listened to, or because you've had a bad experience before with another doctor.

413
00:38:45,688 --> 00:38:48,211
You've lost confidence in doctors and modern medicine.

414
00:38:49,052 --> 00:38:53,418
You read the leaflet that comes with the medicine, and you become afraid of the side effects.

415
00:38:55,239 --> 00:39:01,186
Suppose you go for a job, which every one of your friends and colleagues say suits you, but you don't feel up to it.

416
00:39:01,726 --> 00:39:04,731
You actually get the job, but talk yourself into failure.

417
00:39:06,431 --> 00:39:12,181
You form a relationship with someone, but you can't quite finalize it into a closer partnership or a marriage.

418
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:14,643
You don't trust them, you don't trust yourself.

419
00:39:15,244 --> 00:39:20,112
You feel your past relationships, for one reason or another, didn't last, so why should this one?

420
00:39:21,034 --> 00:39:22,996
Why go through the pain of separation again?

421
00:39:23,838 --> 00:39:26,061
Let's keep the relationship superficial.

422
00:39:27,577 --> 00:39:29,239
It's the same in the spiritual life.

423
00:39:29,978 --> 00:39:32,121
You can't trust the Buddha and his teachings.

424
00:39:32,501 --> 00:39:34,963
It's all very interesting, but you don't try it.

425
00:39:35,625 --> 00:39:38,927
Well, at least, since you're all here on this course, you've overcome that one.

426
00:39:40,489 --> 00:39:43,572
There's a loss of confidence in the teacher, heaven forbid.

427
00:39:44,413 --> 00:39:55,744
Not that there isn't good reason for leaving a teacher, but to leave them because they've asked you to do something, simply because you don't trust them anymore, may be giving into sceptical doubt.

428
00:39:56,922 --> 00:39:58,824
Then, of course, there's doubting oneself.

429
00:39:59,525 --> 00:40:01,989
Everyone else can do the meditation, but I can't.

430
00:40:02,429 --> 00:40:03,371
I'm special that way.

431
00:40:04,612 --> 00:40:06,215
It's an inverted conceit, isn't it?

432
00:40:06,916 --> 00:40:10,061
Instead of being great and wonderful, I'm useless and disgusting.

433
00:40:11,123 --> 00:40:19,014
But such thoughts and feelings about ourselves have to be noted and recognized, watched and observed, experienced and understood.

434
00:40:19,940 --> 00:40:26,045
Such doubts as these can all come up very strongly, and at various times it can be very confusing.

435
00:40:27,047 --> 00:40:35,213
And that's one of the reasons for doubt, the confusion and the anxiety around confusion, those times when we don't know.

436
00:40:35,253 --> 00:40:39,458
We find it very difficult to be in a state of don't know.

437
00:40:39,498 --> 00:40:44,282
If you feel assailed by such thoughts, be sure to approach me about them.

438
00:40:44,802 --> 00:40:49,186
For heaven's sake, don't run away, or at least don't run away without telling me.

439
00:40:50,331 --> 00:40:58,643
As we shall see when we come to talk about the factors of enlightenment, the Buddha wants us to cultivate right doubt, not skeptical doubt.

440
00:40:59,485 --> 00:41:07,376
And right doubt is not to believe what he teaches, but take his teachings as hypotheses that we have to prove right for ourselves.

441
00:41:08,396 --> 00:41:19,291
In other words, he wants us to develop curiosity, an enduring desire to want to know, and specifically to want to understand how we create suffering for ourselves.

442
00:41:20,706 --> 00:41:35,014
So, these are our hindrances, all the alluring sirens of desire, from a simple desire to rest to those vast overwhelming cravings of lust for sex, for money, for fame, for power.

443
00:41:36,177 --> 00:41:41,989
Then there are all the goblins of aversions, from minor irritations to meditation rage.

444
00:41:43,201 --> 00:41:47,831
There are also all those wailing ghosts of anxiety, fear and terror.

445
00:41:49,014 --> 00:42:00,501
Then there are the whirlpools of sloth and torpor taking us down into oblivion, plus the gusts and hurricanes of restlessness from fidgetiness to the manic agitation of guilt.

446
00:42:01,577 --> 00:42:04,463
And finally there are the cold, anxious fogs of doubt.

447
00:42:05,764 --> 00:42:11,715
As they come up, one after the other, the hosts of Mara, we need to accurately acknowledge them.

448
00:42:12,376 --> 00:42:13,297
Be precise.

449
00:42:13,797 --> 00:42:15,221
Then consider what to do.

450
00:42:16,141 --> 00:42:18,326
Don't let them creep up on us, unawares.

451
00:42:18,827 --> 00:42:20,750
That's when they easily ensnare us.

452
00:42:21,190 --> 00:42:26,860
And once we've fallen into the trap, it takes an even greater effort to extricate ourselves.

453
00:42:28,813 --> 00:42:31,516
there was a tale told of a Zen master and a nun.

454
00:42:32,518 --> 00:42:37,182
It seems the nun suddenly began hallucinating, snakes all over the place, and all over her.

455
00:42:38,405 --> 00:42:41,487
They called doctors and other professionals, but to no avail.

456
00:42:42,570 --> 00:42:52,260
Then they called a Zen master, and when he came, he told the nun that he could do nothing unless he knew all the details of the snakes, the color, the length, and so on.

457
00:42:53,222 --> 00:42:55,184
When he came back, they'd all gone.

458
00:42:55,864 --> 00:42:56,105
Why?

459
00:42:56,125 --> 00:42:56,204
Why?

460
00:42:58,126 --> 00:43:07,224
When the Buddha became enlightened, it is said Mara the evil one sent his three daughters, sensual pleasure, lust and boredom, to tempt him.

461
00:43:08,226 --> 00:43:10,010
Now, I've always found this rather interesting.

462
00:43:10,431 --> 00:43:16,523
It suggests the Buddha's prime problem had been these temptations and not one of power, for instance.

463
00:43:16,503 --> 00:43:21,972
And aren't these our own prevalent diseases in an indulgent, affluent society?

464
00:43:23,114 --> 00:43:27,079
Anyway, there came a day when Mara gave up.

465
00:43:27,099 --> 00:43:33,148
His three daughters pleaded with him, give us more time, just a little more time, Dad, and we'll get him.

466
00:43:34,190 --> 00:43:36,875
But Mara said, it's no use, dear daughters.

467
00:43:37,476 --> 00:43:38,978
The Buddha sees me.

468
00:43:39,500 --> 00:43:40,400
The Buddha sees.

469
00:43:40,380 --> 00:43:41,242
Seize me.

470
00:43:41,302 --> 00:43:43,806
You see, the Buddha saw.

471
00:43:44,206 --> 00:43:44,927
He understood.

472
00:43:45,548 --> 00:43:47,271
He was no longer interested.

473
00:43:47,932 --> 00:43:49,815
He simply could not be tempted.

474
00:43:50,657 --> 00:43:52,039
That's where we're heading.

475
00:43:54,123 --> 00:43:58,068
So let's pause here for a moment and allow whatever reflections to arise.

476
00:44:29,182 --> 00:44:47,027
So when these hindrances, desires, aversions, dullness and lethargy, restlessness and guilt and sceptical doubt, when they arise, which are all temptations to lead us away from the practice, we've got to see them, to really acknowledge them.

477
00:44:47,809 --> 00:44:51,454
We've got to remind ourselves that they lead nowhere but to misery.

478
00:44:52,315 --> 00:44:58,784
We've got to see that if we don't bring such considerations to mind, the old conditionings will take over

479
00:44:59,744 --> 00:45:05,273
And whenever they do that, we don't simply give in to temptations, we reinforce them.

480
00:45:05,833 --> 00:45:11,262
We condition ourselves back into the same old unskillful ways and worse.

481
00:45:12,605 --> 00:45:21,498
The last words of the Buddha were, appamadena sampadeta, strive on with diligence, with vigilance.

482
00:45:22,659 --> 00:45:27,164
Think how vigilant you would be if you knew a murderer was stalking you.

483
00:45:27,925 --> 00:45:32,429
Well, we have to have that level of vigilance without the paranoia.

484
00:45:33,769 --> 00:45:35,271
So we've got to keep awake.

485
00:45:36,411 --> 00:45:51,164
One day we shall surely arrive at that state where Mara and all his evil, malevolent, wicked daughters and sons will slink off defeated, and with them will go all our sufferings.

486
00:45:53,288 --> 00:45:58,054
So even though these opening days are hard, there's no way for it but to go on.

487
00:45:59,034 --> 00:45:59,335
Onward.

488
00:46:01,478 --> 00:46:13,012
May your devotion to moment to moment vigilance and mindfulness and your wise parrying of the blows of Mara the evil one bear you great fruit.

489
00:46:14,253 --> 00:46:19,059
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.
